description: From Middle English teneful, from Old English tēonful, tēonfull (“grievous; vexatious; troublesome; woeful”), equivalent to teen +‎ -ful.

adjectives.description: teenful (comparative more teenful, superlative most teenful)

entries.meaning: (poetic, dialectal, archaic or obsolete) Full of grief; harmful; afflicted; troublesome; vexatious
examples: O, whither tends the lamentable spite Of this world's teenful apprehension, Which understands all things amiss, whose light Shines not amidst the dark of their dissension?
